    "rag_evidence": [
      {
        "content": "SWC-107: Reentrancy\n\nOne of the major dangers of calling external contracts is that they can take over the control flow. In the reentrancy attack, a malicious contract calls back into the calling contract before the first invocation of the function is finished, so changes to state that should have prevented the re-call have not yet occurred. Remediation: finish all internal work (state changes) before calling external functions; use a reentrancy guard (mutex).",
        "doc_id": "SWC-107",
        "chunk_id": 0,
        "total_chunks": 1,
        "metadata": {
          "protocol": "unknown",
          "date": "2020-01-01",
          "vuln_type": "reentrancy",
          "severity": "high",
          "loss_usd": 0,
          "chain": "",
          "url": "https://swcregistry.io/docs/SWC-107",
          "source": "swc_registry",
          "chunk_id": 0,
          "total_chunks": 1,
          "doc_id": "SWC-107"
        },
        "score": 0.03278688524590164
      },
      {
        "content": "Reentrancy via ERC777 tokensReceived hook in deposit/withdraw\n\nA pool that calls an external ERC777 token transfer before updating internal accounting is reentrant: the recipient's tokensReceived hook re-enters withdraw() while the user's balance is still recorded, draining funds. Root cause: violation of checks-effects-interactions. Fix: update state before the external transfer, or add a nonReentrant guard. ERC20 tokens with transfer hooks (ERC777) make 'safe' ERC20 flows exploitable.",
        "doc_id": "code4rena-reentrancy-erc777-hook",
        "chunk_id": 0,
        "total_chunks": 1,
        "metadata": {
          "protocol": "Generic AMM",
